  <discussion>C. L. Hitchcock (1941) treated Draba chamissonis as a variety of D. nivalis and listed it from British Columbia; R. C. Rollins (1993) did not mention the taxon at any rank. The limited North American material of D. chamissonis that we examined is all from Alaska. The species strongly resembles D. nivalis, from which it is distinguished by having (1 or) 2–7 broadly ovate cauline leaves, proximalmost fruiting pedicels (4–)6–13(–20) mm, petals 1.5–2 mm wide, and fruits 1.1–1.6(–2) mm wide. By contrast, D. nivalis has one ovate or oblong cauline leaf, or none, proximalmost fruiting pedicels 1–4.5(–8) mm, petals 0.8–1.4 mm wide, and fruits 1.5–2.2 mm wide.</discussion>
